                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="false">
                                <p>Modern binding. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/> in light brown leather, with nine double strands of thread fastening the quires. On the the back flap a note with text in black ink in a modern hand: <quote xml:lang="la">Processus Canonisationis Beatae Katarinae 1477</quote>. On the inside a note in pencil: <quote>Häftad 1987 i befintliga hål</quote> followed by a signature.</p>
                            </binding>
                            <binding contemporary="true">
                                <p>The original red velvet wrappers, with green silk on the <locus from="Cover_inside" to="Cover_inside" scheme="folios"/>, described by e.g. <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107267">Collijn (1943)</title>
                                        <citedRange from="xxii" to="xxii" unit="page"/>
                                    </bibl> and <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107256">Odelberg (1965)</title>
                                        <citedRange from="63" to="67" unit="page"/>
                                    </bibl>. The velvet is woven in a pomegranate pattern and embroidered with ornaments in gold and silver. On the edges a border in gold and silver thread, probably woven in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100205">Vadstena monastery</placeName>. On the spine an embroidery with green and red silk threads, originally fastening the quires. Another manuscript, the so-called <quote>Libellus rubeus</quote> containing the legend and miracles of St Katarina, was originally kept within the wrappers, and is mentioned on <locus from="87r" to="87r" scheme="folios"/> (<quote xml:lang="la">in quodam paruo libello Rubeo continente xxxvi folia</quote>); this manuscript is now in the <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100248">Ossolineum</placeName> library (Poland). The rectangular holes on the spine indicate that the seals were originally fastened here, as well as on the lower part of the front cover. <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107267">Collijn (1943)</title>
                                        <citedRange from="xii" to="xii" unit="page"/>
                                    </bibl> mentions remnants of green wax (no longer visible) on the front cover. Holes for the threads of the seals are visible near the spine. The wrappers were repaired in <date when="1960">1960.</date>
                                </p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="360" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="240" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100081">Sweden</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate when="1477">1477</origDate>
                            </p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The volume was produced in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100101">Vadstena</placeName>, <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100106">Strängnäs</placeName> and other places where witnesses were heard during the canonisation process. It was sent to <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100070">Rome</placeName> and may have been kept in the <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100249">Birgitta house</placeName> for some time. In the 17th century, the manuscript was kept at the Royal Castle in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100243">Cracow</placeName>, see <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107267">Collijn (1943)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="xxv" to="xxv" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>. It was found at the Dominican convent <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100250">Ad Sanctam Trinitatem</placeName> in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100243">Cracow</placeName> by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102567"> Beda Dudík </persName> in <date when="1865"/>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Purchased by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/100853"> G. E. Klemming </persName> for the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> in <date when="1873"/>. The acquistion process is described in <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107267">Collijn (1943)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="xxiv" to="xxv" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl> and <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107256">Odelberg (1965)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="59" to="61" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
